    "A supply shock (like a disruption in key materials) forces factories to slow down, so production and hiring drop first and the rest of the economy follows.",
    "After a long run-up, businesses get too optimistic and overbuild/invest too much; the correction hits demand, inventories pile up, and contraction accelerates.",
    "A policy or external demand boost earlier in the year keeps things strong, but it fades over time; without sustained support, spending slows, moving the economy toward the next downturn."
  ],
  "scenario": "Your retail chain’s monthly sales have been sliding for three straight months, even though you didn’t change prices or promotions. In the same period, suppliers report longer delivery times, and several local factories have started cutting shifts. Your dashboard also shows customer refunds rising and new hiring freezing across nearby branches."
}

{
